    story: '''
Amaterasu Omikami lahir dari mata kiri Izanagi, dewa pencipta purba, ketika ia melakukan ritual penyucian diri (misogi) di muara sungai dekat Tachibana, wilayah Himuka, sekembalinya dari negeri kematian Yomi. Bersama kedua saudaranya yang lahir dari penyucian yang sama, Tsukuyomi dari mata kanan dan Susanoo dari hidung, Amaterasu dianggap sebagai yang termulia di antara ketiganya, dikenal bersama sebagai Mihashira no Uzunomiko, Tiga Anak Mulia. Izanagi begitu bangga dan gembira menyaksikan cahaya luar biasa yang dipancarkan putrinya sehingga ia melepas kalung permata miliknya sendiri dan mengalungkannya pada Amaterasu, sekaligus menyerahkan kekuasaan penuh atas Takamagahara, Dataran Tinggi Langit tempat bersemayamnya para dewa.

Sebagai penguasa Takamagahara, Amaterasu memerintah sebagai dewi matahari tertinggi yang cahayanya menghidupi seluruh alam, sekaligus menjadi figur otoritas moral dan tatanan di antara para dewa langit. Ia digambarkan sebagai penenun yang tekun di anjungan tenunnya sendiri, dan erat dikaitkan dengan cermin suci Yata no Kagami, yang kelak menjadi salah satu dari Tiga Pusaka Suci kekaisaran Jepang. Melalui cucunya, Ninigi no Mikoto, yang turun ke bumi membawa cermin, pedang, dan permata sebagai lambang kekuasaan, Amaterasu diyakini sebagai leluhur langsung garis kekaisaran Jepang, sehingga setiap kaisar dianggap sebagai keturunannya. Kuil utamanya, Ise Jingu, tetap menjadi tempat pemujaan paling suci dalam kepercayaan Shinto hingga saat ini.

Kisah paling terkenal tentang Amaterasu adalah peristiwa Ame no Iwato, gua batu surgawi. Setelah Susanoo mengamuk di Takamagahara, merusak sawah, mengotori aula pemujaannya, dan melemparkan kuda yang dikuliti ke ruang tenun hingga menewaskan salah satu pelayannya, Amaterasu yang ketakutan dan berduka bersembunyi di dalam gua, menutup pintunya dengan batu besar hingga dunia tenggelam dalam kegelapan total. Para dewa berkumpul cemas di Ame no Yasukawara, sungai suci di Takamagahara, hingga Ame no Uzume menari secara liar dan jenaka di depan gua sehingga membuat ratusan ribu dewa tertawa terbahak-bahak. Didorong rasa penasaran mendengar gelak tawa di tengah kegelapan, Amaterasu mengintip keluar dan langsung ditarik oleh dewa Ame no Tajikarao, mengembalikan cahaya ke seluruh jagat. Peristiwa ini tetap menjadi salah satu mitos pemulihan cahaya paling dihormati dalam tradisi Shinto.''',
    storyEn: '''
Amaterasu Omikami was born from the left eye of Izanagi, the primordial creator god, as he performed a purification ritual (misogi) at the mouth of a river near Tachibana in the land of Himuka, having just returned from Yomi, the realm of the dead. Alongside the two siblings born from that same rite, Tsukuyomi from his right eye and Susanoo from his nose, she was honored as the most radiant of the three, together known as the Mihashira no Uzunomiko, the Three Noble Children. So overjoyed was Izanagi at the brilliance she gave off that he removed the jeweled necklace from his own neck, placed it upon her, and granted her full dominion over Takamagahara, the High Celestial Plain where the heavenly gods dwell.

As ruler of Takamagahara, Amaterasu governs as the supreme sun goddess whose light sustains the entire world, and stands as a figure of moral authority and cosmic order among the heavenly gods. She is depicted as a diligent weaver at her own loom hall, and is closely associated with the sacred mirror Yata no Kagami, which later became one of the Three Sacred Treasures of the Japanese imperial regalia. Through her grandson Ninigi no Mikoto, who descended to earth bearing the mirror, sword, and jewel as emblems of rightful rule, Amaterasu is regarded as the direct divine ancestress of Japan's imperial line, with every emperor traditionally considered her descendant. Her principal shrine, Ise Jingu, remains the holiest site of worship in Shinto belief to this day.

Amaterasu's most celebrated myth is the episode of Ame no Iwato, the heavenly rock cave. After Susanoo rampaged through Takamagahara, tearing down rice paddies, defiling her sacred hall, and hurling a flayed horse into her weaving chamber and killing one of her attendants, a terrified and grief-stricken Amaterasu shut herself inside a cave, sealing the entrance with a massive boulder and plunging the world into total darkness. The assembled gods gathered anxiously at Ame no Yasukawara, a sacred river in Takamagahara, until Ame no Uzume performed a wild, comic dance before the cave that sent the eight hundred myriad gods into thunderous laughter. Curious how there could be laughter amid such darkness, Amaterasu peered outside and was immediately pulled free by the god Ame no Tajikarao, restoring light to the entire world. The episode remains one of Shinto's most revered myths of light's return.''',
