    story: '''
Susanoo no Mikoto lahir dari hidung Izanagi, pelengkap terakhir dari Tiga Anak Mulia yang tercipta ketika sang dewa pencipta menyucikan diri di sungai dekat Tachibana sepulang dari Yomi. Sebagai anugerah, Izanagi memberinya kekuasaan atas lautan, namun alih-alih menjalankan tugasnya, Susanoo justru menangis meraung-raung tanpa henti karena rindu pada ibunya, Izanami, yang telah tiada dan bersemayam di Yomi. Tangisannya yang dahsyat membuat gunung-gunung gundul dan sungai-sungai mengering, hingga Izanagi yang murka mengusirnya dari kediamannya. Sebelum benar-benar pergi, Susanoo memutuskan untuk berpamitan kepada kakaknya, Amaterasu, di Takamagahara, sebuah kunjungan yang justru menjadi awal dari salah satu babak paling kacau dalam mitologi Jepang.

Susanoo dikenal sebagai dewa badai, angin topan, dan lautan, sosok yang liar, impulsif, serta penuh gejolak emosi, sangat kontras dengan sifat kakaknya yang tenang dan teratur. Ketika tiba di Takamagahara, langkahnya membuat seisi negeri bergetar hebat sehingga Amaterasu mengira ia datang untuk merebut takhta, memaksa keduanya melakukan sumpah ukei dengan saling menukar benda pusaka untuk membuktikan niat baik masing-masing. Meski sumpah itu terbukti tulus, watak liar Susanoo segera meletus kembali: ia merusak petak-petak sawah suci, mengotori ruang persembahan kakaknya, dan melemparkan seekor kuda yang telah dikuliti hidup-hidup ke dalam ruang tenun hingga menewaskan seorang pelayan, kekacauan yang secara langsung mendorong Amaterasu bersembunyi di gua Ame no Iwato dan membuatnya diusir selamanya dari Takamagahara.

Setelah diusir ke bumi dan turun di wilayah Izumo, Susanoo bertemu sepasang suami istri tua yang menangis karena putri bungsu mereka, Kushinada Hime, akan menjadi santapan terakhir Yamata no Orochi, ular raksasa berkepala dan berekor delapan yang telah melahap tujuh saudarinya. Susanoo menawarkan diri membunuh sang ular dengan syarat dapat menikahi Kushinada Hime, mengubah sang putri menjadi sisir agar aman, lalu meminta pasangan tua itu menyiapkan delapan tong sake keras. Yamata no Orochi yang rakus meminum semua sake hingga mabuk dan tertidur, memberi Susanoo kesempatan untuk mencincangnya hingga mati. Dari salah satu ekornya, ia menemukan pedang sakti Kusanagi, yang kemudian dipersembahkannya kepada Amaterasu sebagai tanda rekonsiliasi. Kemenangan ini mengubah Susanoo dari sosok pembuat onar menjadi pahlawan penebus dosa, leluhur para penguasa Izumo, termasuk cucunya, Okuninushi.''',
    storyEn: '''
Susanoo no Mikoto was born from Izanagi's nose, the last of the Three Noble Children brought forth when the creator god purified himself in a river near Tachibana after returning from Yomi. As his portion of dominion, Izanagi granted him rule over the sea, yet instead of tending to his duties, Susanoo wept and wailed without end, consumed by longing for his dead mother Izanami in Yomi. His thunderous crying withered the mountains bare and dried up the rivers, until a furious Izanagi banished him from his home. Before departing for good, Susanoo resolved to bid farewell to his sister Amaterasu in Takamagahara, a visit that would instead ignite one of the most chaotic chapters in all of Japanese mythology.

Susanoo is known as the god of storms, tempests, and the sea, a wild, impulsive, and deeply emotional figure who stands in sharp contrast to his sister's calm and orderly nature. When he arrived in Takamagahara, his footsteps shook the land so violently that Amaterasu suspected he had come to seize her throne, prompting the two to perform the ukei oath, exchanging sacred treasures to prove their sincerity toward one another. Though the oath proved genuine, Susanoo's wild temperament soon erupted again: he tore down the ridges of the sacred rice paddies, defiled his sister's ceremonial hall, and hurled a horse flayed alive into her weaving chamber, killing one of her attendants, a rampage that drove Amaterasu into hiding within the cave of Ame no Iwato and saw him banished from Takamagahara forever.

Cast down to earth and landing in the province of Izumo, Susanoo came upon an elderly couple weeping because their youngest daughter, Kushinada Hime, was about to become the final meal of Yamata no Orochi, an eight-headed, eight-tailed serpent that had already devoured her seven sisters. Susanoo offered to slay the beast in exchange for her hand in marriage, transformed her into a comb for safekeeping, and instructed the couple to brew eight vats of potent sake. The gluttonous serpent drank itself into a stupor, giving Susanoo the opening to hack it to pieces. Within one of its tails he discovered the sacred sword Kusanagi, which he later presented to Amaterasu as a gesture of reconciliation. The victory transformed Susanoo from a destructive troublemaker into a redeeming hero, and he became the ancestor of Izumo's line of rulers, including his descendant Okuninushi.''',
