Futsunushi dipuja sebagai dewa pedang dan peperangan, figur yang hampir selalu tampil berdampingan dengan Takemikazuchi sebagai sepasang dewa perang utusan Takamagahara. Kuil utamanya, Katori Jingu, berdiri tidak jauh dari Kashima Jingu, kuil Takemikazuchi, dan keduanya sejak lama menjadi tujuan ziarah para pendekar serta pendiri aliran seni bela diri pedang Jepang, termasuk salah satu aliran tertua, Katori Shinto-ryu, yang mengaku mendapat restu langsung dari sang dewa. Meski kerap tampak sebagai pendamping Takemikazuchi, Futsunushi memiliki kedudukan setara sebagai eksekutor kehendak para dewa langit, dihormati atas ketegasan, kesetiaan, dan keahlian tempurnya yang tanpa cela.

Sebagaimana Takemikazuchi, Futsunushi turun ke Izumo dalam misi kuni-yuzuri untuk menuntut penyerahan kekuasaan bumi dari Okuninushi, menjadikan keduanya sepasang duta yang berhasil menuntaskan misi setelah dua utusan sebelumnya gagal. Sebagian riwayat Nihon Shoki bahkan menempatkan Futsunushi sebagai tokoh utama dalam perundingan tersebut, sejajar dengan peran Takemikazuchi dalam versi Kojiki. Nama dan kekuatan Futsunushi kembali muncul dalam legenda kemudian, ketika pedang suci bernama Futsu no Mitama diturunkan dari langit untuk menyelamatkan pasukan Kaisar Jimmu yang lumpuh tak berdaya di hutan Kumano dalam perjalanan penaklukannya ke timur. Berkat kisah ini, Futsunushi diyakini terus menjaga garis kekaisaran Jepang bahkan lama setelah era para dewa berakhir, menjadikannya simbol abadi kekuatan militer yang melindungi bangsa.''',
    storyEn: '''
Futsunushi no Kami arose from the very same sacred event as Takemikazuchi: when blood from the sword Izanagi used to slay Kagutsuchi, the god of fire, spattered onto the surrounding rocks and gave rise to a number of formidable deities. In the Nihon Shoki, Futsunushi is portrayed as so deeply fused with that very sword that he is often described as its deified spirit, or mitama, and his name, "Futsu," is said to echo the crisp, decisive sound of a blade cutting cleanly through its target. Born directly out of a sacred weapon, Futsunushi is a god whose very identity is nearly inseparable from the sword, from raw power, and from a true warrior's precision.

Futsunushi is worshipped as a god of swords and war, a figure almost always paired with Takemikazuchi as one of two great warrior-envoys of Takamagahara. His principal shrine, Katori Jingu, stands not far from Kashima Jingu, the shrine of Takemikazuchi, and for centuries the two sites have drawn pilgrimages from swordsmen and founders of Japanese martial traditions, including one of the oldest surviving schools, Katori Shinto-ryu, which claims to have received the god's own blessing. Though frequently cast as Takemikazuchi's companion, Futsunushi holds equal standing as an enforcer of the heavenly gods' will, honored for his resolve, loyalty, and flawless skill in combat.

Like Takemikazuchi, Futsunushi descended to Izumo on the mission of kuni-yuzuri to demand the surrender of earthly rule from Okuninushi, and the two together succeeded where two earlier envoys had failed. Some traditions within the Nihon Shoki even cast Futsunushi as the lead figure in that negotiation, standing on equal footing with the role Takemikazuchi plays in the Kojiki's version of events. Futsunushi's name and power resurface in a later legend, when a sacred sword called Futsu no Mitama was sent down from heaven to rescue the forces of Emperor Jimmu, left powerless in the forests of Kumano during his eastward campaign of conquest. Through this tale, Futsunushi is believed to have continued watching over Japan's imperial line long after the age of the gods had ended, making him an enduring symbol of the martial strength that protects the nation.''',
