    story: '''
Okuninushi, yang semula bernama Onamuchi, adalah keturunan Susanoo beberapa generasi dan salah satu dari delapan puluh saudara (Yasogami) yang kerap memperlakukannya dengan buruk sebagai adik bungsu yang lemah. Namanya mulai dikenal ketika ia menolong seekor kelinci putih Pulau Inaba yang telah dikuliti akibat tertipu oleh saran licik saudara-saudaranya, dengan mengajarkannya membasuh diri di air tawar lalu berguling di serbuk sari gelagah. Berkat kebaikan hati itu, sang kelinci meramalkan bahwa Onamuchi, bukan saudara-saudaranya yang congkak, akan memenangkan hati Putri Yagami. Ramalan ini membakar amarah para Yasogami, yang kemudian membunuhnya dua kali dengan cara licik, namun setiap kali ia berhasil dihidupkan kembali berkat pertolongan ibunya dan dua dewi kerang.

Untuk menghindari amukan saudara-saudaranya, Onamuchi melarikan diri ke Ne no Katasukuni, negeri bawah tanah tempat Susanoo bersemayam, dan jatuh cinta pada putrinya, Suseri Hime. Susanoo mengujinya dengan serangkaian cobaan mematikan, mulai dari ruangan berisi ular, ruangan berisi lipan dan tawon, hingga padang yang sengaja dibakar, namun berkat syal sakti pemberian Suseri Hime dan pertolongan seekor tikus, Onamuchi berhasil melewati semuanya. Ketika akhirnya ia melarikan diri bersama Suseri Hime sambil membawa busur, pedang, dan kecapi pusaka milik Susanoo, sang mertua yang murka justru terkesan oleh keteguhan hatinya, mengejarnya hanya sampai batas Yomi, lalu merestui pernikahan mereka seraya memberinya nama baru, Okuninushi, "Penguasa Agung Negeri", dan menyuruhnya menaklukkan para Yasogami untuk memerintah bumi.

Sebagai penguasa Izumo, Okuninushi dibantu oleh dewa mungil Sukunabikona, yang datang mengarungi laut dengan perahu dari kulit polong, untuk bersama-sama membangun negeri: mengembangkan pertanian, memperkenalkan pengobatan, dan menyusun mantra-mantra sihir demi melindungi manusia. Setelah Sukunabikona pergi ke negeri abadi, Okuninushi melanjutkan sendiri karya besar itu hingga menjadi penguasa paling dihormati di bumi. Namun ketika Takemikazuchi dan Futsunushi datang menuntut penyerahan kekuasaan atas nama Amaterasu, Okuninushi memilih jalan damai: ia menyerahkan kendali dunia yang tampak kepada garis keturunan langit, dengan syarat dibangunkan istana megah setinggi istana para dewa, cikal bakal Kuil Izumo Taisha, sementara ia sendiri tetap memegang kuasa atas dunia yang tak tampak, termasuk urusan takdir dan jodoh. Karena itulah Okuninushi hingga kini paling dipuja sebagai dewa perjodohan dan ikatan hidup manusia.''',
    storyEn: '''
Okuninushi, originally named Onamuchi, was a descendant of Susanoo several generations removed and one of eighty brothers, the Yasogami, who routinely mistreated him as their weak, youngest sibling. He first won renown when he rescued the White Hare of Inaba, an animal that had been skinned raw after falling for his brothers' cruel trick, teaching it instead to bathe in fresh water and roll in the pollen of cattail reeds to heal. In gratitude, the hare prophesied that Onamuchi, rather than his arrogant brothers, would win the hand of Princess Yagami. The prophecy enraged the Yasogami, who murdered him twice through cunning schemes, but each time he was restored to life through his mother's pleading and the aid of two shellfish goddesses.

To escape his brothers' fury, Onamuchi fled to Ne no Katasukuni, the underworld realm ruled by Susanoo, and fell in love with his daughter, Suseri Hime. Susanoo subjected him to a string of deadly trials, a chamber filled with snakes, another swarming with centipedes and wasps, and a field set deliberately ablaze, but with the aid of Suseri Hime's magical scarf and a helpful mouse, Onamuchi survived every one. When he finally fled together with Suseri Hime, carrying off Susanoo's sacred bow, sword, and koto, his furious father-in-law found himself impressed instead by his resolve, pursuing him only as far as the border of Yomi before blessing their marriage, bestowing on him the new name Okuninushi, "Great Lord of the Land," and charging him to conquer the Yasogami and rule the earth.

As ruler of Izumo, Okuninushi was joined by the tiny deity Sukunabikona, who arrived crossing the sea in a boat made from a bean pod, and together the two built up the land, developing agriculture, introducing medicine, and devising magical incantations to protect humankind. After Sukunabikona departed for the eternal land, Okuninushi carried the great work forward alone until he became the most respected ruler on earth. But when Takemikazuchi and Futsunushi arrived demanding the surrender of power on Amaterasu's behalf, Okuninushi chose the path of peace: he ceded control of the visible world to the heavenly lineage, on the condition that a magnificent palace be built for him as tall as the dwellings of the gods, the origin of Izumo Taisha, while he himself retained authority over the unseen world, including matters of fate and marriage. For this reason, Okuninushi remains today one of the most beloved gods of matchmaking and human bonds.''',
