  God(
    id: '305',
    name: 'Urashima Taro',
    mythology: 'Japanese',
    title: 'Nelayan dari Istana Naga',
    titleEn: 'The Fisherman of the Dragon Palace',
    symbol: '🐢',
    powers: ['Kebaikan Hati', 'Istana Naga', 'Perjalanan Waktu', 'Rasa Ingin Tahu', 'Kefanaan'],
    powersEn: ['Kindness', 'Dragon Palace', 'Passage of Time', 'Curiosity', 'Mortality'],
    story: '''
Urashima Taro adalah seorang nelayan muda yang tinggal di sebuah desa pesisir, dikenal luas karena kebaikan hatinya kepada semua makhluk. Suatu sore sepulang melaut, ia mendapati sekelompok anak-anak sedang menyiksa seekor kura-kura kecil di tepi pantai, melemparinya dan memukulinya untuk hiburan semata. Merasa iba, Urashima Taro membujuk anak-anak itu agar berhenti dan menukar kura-kura tersebut dengan beberapa koin, lalu dengan lembut melepaskannya kembali ke laut lepas. Ia tidak menyangka bahwa tindakan kecil penuh kasih itu akan membuka pintu menuju petualangan paling menakjubkan sekaligus paling menyedihkan dalam hidupnya, sebuah kisah yang telah dituturkan sejak zaman Nihon Shoki dan tercatat pula dalam kumpulan puisi kuno Man'yoshu.

Beberapa hari kemudian, seekor kura-kura besar muncul di dekat perahunya dan berbicara, mengaku sebagai utusan dari kura-kura yang telah ia selamatkan, lalu mengundangnya untuk berkunjung ke Istana Naga di dasar laut, Ryugu-jo, sebagai ucapan terima kasih. Urashima Taro naik ke punggung kura-kura itu dan dibawa turun menembus air hingga tiba di istana megah yang berkilauan seperti disusun dari karang dan mutiara. Di sana ia disambut oleh Otohime, putri jelita sang dewa laut Ryujin, yang ternyata adalah wujud asli kura-kura yang ia tolong. Selama berhari-hari ia dijamu dengan pesta mewah, tarian ikan-ikan berwarna-warni, dan keindahan dunia bawah laut yang tiada tara, hingga ia sepenuhnya lupa waktu dan kerinduannya pada kampung halaman.

Setelah apa yang terasa hanya beberapa hari, Urashima Taro mulai merindukan desa dan orang tuanya, lalu memohon izin untuk pulang. Otohime dengan berat hati mengizinkannya, namun membekalinya sebuah kotak berhias bernama tamatebako dan berpesan agar ia tidak pernah membukanya apa pun yang terjadi. Begitu tiba di daratan, Urashima Taro tidak mengenali desanya sama sekali; rumahnya lenyap, dan tak seorang pun mengenal namanya, sebab ternyata ratusan tahun telah berlalu selama ia berada di istana laut, dan seluruh keluarga serta sahabatnya telah lama tiada. Dilanda putus asa dan kebingungan, ia melanggar janjinya dan membuka tamatebako; dari dalamnya mengepul asap putih yang seketika mengubahnya menjadi lelaki tua renta, sebab kotak itu ternyata menyimpan seluruh usianya yang tertunda. Kisah Urashima Taro sejak itu menjadi renungan mendalam tentang waktu, kehilangan, dan akibat dari melanggar janji, salah satu dongeng paling dikenang dalam khazanah sastra rakyat Jepang.''',
    storyEn: '''
Urashima Taro was a young fisherman from a coastal village, well known among his neighbors for his gentle kindness toward every living creature. One evening, returning from a day at sea, he came upon a group of children tormenting a small turtle on the beach, throwing stones at it and beating it purely for amusement. Moved to pity, he persuaded the children to stop, paid them a few coins for the turtle, and gently released it back into the open sea. He had no way of knowing that this small act of compassion would open the door to the most wondrous, and ultimately most sorrowful, adventure of his life, a story told since the days of the Nihon Shoki and recorded as well in the ancient poetry collection Man'yoshu.

A few days later, a great turtle surfaced beside his boat and spoke, explaining that it was a messenger from the very turtle he had saved, and invited him to visit the undersea Dragon Palace, Ryugu-jo, as a token of gratitude. Urashima Taro climbed onto the turtle's back and was carried down through the water until he reached a magnificent palace that seemed built of coral and pearl. There he was welcomed by Otohime, the beautiful daughter of the sea god Ryujin, who turned out to be the true form of the turtle he had rescued. For what seemed like days he was feted with lavish banquets, dances performed by shimmering fish, and undersea wonders beyond compare, and in that enchantment he entirely lost track of time and of his longing for home.

After what felt like only a few days, Urashima Taro began to miss his village and his aging parents, and asked leave to return. Otohime reluctantly agreed, but gave him an ornate box called the tamatebako and warned him never to open it, whatever happened. The moment he set foot on land, he could not recognize his own village; his house was gone, and no one knew his name, for hundreds of years had in fact passed while he dwelled in the palace beneath the sea, and his family and every friend he had known were long since dead. Overwhelmed by grief and confusion, he broke his promise and opened the tamatebako; white smoke curled out and instantly transformed him into a frail old man, for the box had all along held the years he had been spared. Urashima Taro's story has endured ever since as a profound meditation on time, loss, and the price of breaking a promise, one of the most cherished tales in Japanese folklore.''',
