    powersEn: ['Superhuman Strength', 'Animal Friendship', 'Wrestling', 'Vitality', 'Courage'],
    story: '''
Kintaro lahir dan dibesarkan seorang diri oleh ibunya di lereng Gunung Ashigara yang terpencil, jauh dari keramaian dunia manusia. Dalam sebagian versi legenda, ibunya, yang dikenal dengan nama Yaegiri, mengungsi ke pegunungan tersebut sambil mengandungnya, dan sebagian cerita bahkan menyebut Kintaro sebagai anak dari dewa guntur, menjelaskan kekuatannya yang luar biasa sejak bayi. Sejak kecil ia digambarkan bertubuh gempal kemerahan dengan tenaga yang jauh melampaui anak-anak seusianya, mampu mencabut pohon dan mengangkat batu besar hanya dengan tangan kosong. Karena kulitnya yang merona serta semangatnya yang membara bagai emas, ia dijuluki Kintaro, "Sang Bocah Emas", dan tumbuh menjadi anak gunung yang riang, jujur, dan penuh rasa ingin tahu terhadap dunia di sekitarnya.

Tanpa teman sebaya manusia, Kintaro tumbuh bersama binatang-binatang hutan sebagai sahabat sekaligus lawan bermainnya: ia bergulat dengan beruang, berlomba lari dengan rusa, dan memanjat tebing bersama monyet-monyet gunung, memperlakukan mereka semua sebagai saudara. Kisah paling terkenal menggambarkannya menunggangi seekor beruang besar layaknya kuda tunggangan sekaligus mengalahkannya dalam pertandingan gulat sumo, serta bergulat dengan seekor ikan mas raksasa di sungai pegunungan. Ia biasanya digambarkan membawa kapak besar (masakari) di pundaknya dan mengenakan kain perut bertuliskan aksara "kin" yang berarti emas, gambaran yang hingga kini menjadi salah satu citra paling dikenal dalam seni rakyat Jepang.

Kekuatan dan keberanian luar biasa Kintaro akhirnya terdengar oleh samurai terkenal Minamoto no Yorimitsu, yang kebetulan melintasi Gunung Ashigara dan menyaksikan sendiri kehebatannya menaklukkan binatang buas. Terkesan, sang samurai membawa Kintaro turun ke ibu kota dan mengangkatnya sebagai pengikut, memberinya nama dewasa Sakata no Kintoki. Di bawah nama itu, ia kelak menjadi salah satu dari Empat Raja Pengawal (Shitenno) paling dipercaya Yorimitsu, turut serta dalam petualangan legendaris menumpas iblis Shuten-doji di Gunung Oe. Hingga sekarang, Kintaro tetap menjadi simbol kesehatan, kekuatan, dan pertumbuhan yang penuh semangat bagi anak laki-laki Jepang; wajahnya yang ceria menghiasi boneka dan panji-panji yang dipajang setiap tanggal 5 Mei dalam perayaan Hari Anak, mendoakan agar setiap anak tumbuh sekuat dan sesehat dirinya.''',
    storyEn: '''
Kintaro was born and raised in solitude by his mother on the slopes of remote Mount Ashigara, far from the bustle of human settlements. In some versions of the legend his mother, known as Yaegiri, fled into the mountains while pregnant with him, and certain tellings even claim Kintaro was the son of a thunder god, accounting for his extraordinary strength from infancy. From early childhood he was depicted as a plump, ruddy-skinned boy whose power far outstripped that of any ordinary child, able to uproot trees and hoist boulders with his bare hands. Because of his glowing red complexion and his fiery, golden-hearted spirit, he came to be called Kintaro, "the Golden Boy," and grew into a cheerful, honest child of the mountains, endlessly curious about the world around him.

With no human playmates, Kintaro grew up among the animals of the forest, who became both his companions and his sparring partners: he wrestled bears, raced deer, and scaled cliffs alongside mountain monkeys, treating every creature as a sibling. The most famous episodes show him riding a great bear as though it were his horse and besting it in a sumo match, as well as wrestling a giant carp in a mountain river. He is traditionally depicted carrying a large ax (masakari) over his shoulder and wearing a belly wrap bearing the character "kin," meaning gold, an image that remains one of the most instantly recognizable in Japanese folk art to this day.

Word of Kintaro's astonishing strength and courage eventually reached the celebrated samurai Minamoto no Yorimitsu, who happened to pass through Mount Ashigara and witnessed for himself the boy's mastery over wild beasts. Impressed, the samurai brought Kintaro down to the capital and took him on as a retainer, giving him the adult name Sakata no Kintoki. Under that name he would go on to become one of Yorimitsu's most trusted Four Guardian Kings (Shitenno), joining the legendary expedition that defeated the demon Shuten-doji on Mount Oe. To this day Kintaro remains a beloved symbol of health, strength, and vigorous growth for Japanese boys; his beaming face adorns dolls and banners displayed every May 5th during Children's Day, a wish that every child grow as strong and hale as he did.''',
